# Backend Architecture Standard

## Purpose

This rule defines the backend architecture standards for the project.

Its purpose is to ensure that every backend feature is:

- Maintainable
- Predictable
- Testable
- Secure
- Scalable
- Modular

This rule applies to every backend module.

---

# Scope

This rule covers:

- Controllers
- Application Services
- Domain Services
- Repositories
- Infrastructure
- API Layer
- Business Logic
- Dependency Flow

It does not define:

- Database implementation
- Frontend architecture
- Deployment
- Infrastructure configuration

Those topics have dedicated rules.

---

# Backend Philosophy

Backend exists to implement business capabilities.

Technology serves business.

Business never serves technology.

Always model the business first.

Implementation details come second.

---

# Architectural Style

The backend follows:

- Modular Monolith
- Clean Architecture
- Domain Driven Design
- SOLID
- DRY
- KISS
- YAGNI

Every feature must respect these principles.

---

# Feature-First Organization

Organize backend by business capability.

Correct:

Catalog

Orders

Checkout

Payments

Customers

Inventory

Search

Incorrect:

Controllers

Services

Repositories

Helpers

Utils

Technology-first organization is prohibited.

---

# Layered Architecture

Every feature contains four logical layers.

Presentation

↓

Application

↓

Domain

↓

Infrastructure

Dependencies always point inward.

---

# Presentation Layer

Responsibilities:

- Receive requests
- Validate transport objects
- Call application services
- Return responses

Controllers must remain thin.

Controllers never contain business logic.

Controllers never access repositories directly.

Controllers never manipulate the database.

---

# Application Layer

Responsibilities:

- Execute use cases
- Coordinate workflows
- Manage transactions
- Invoke domain objects
- Publish events

Application Services orchestrate.

They do not implement business rules.

---

# Domain Layer

The Domain layer owns:

- Business rules
- Entities
- Value Objects
- Aggregates
- Domain Services
- Domain Events

Everything critical to business belongs here.

The Domain layer knows nothing about:

- HTTP
- SQL
- Frameworks
- ORM
- Cache
- External APIs

---

# Infrastructure Layer

Infrastructure implements:

- Database
- Cache
- Email
- Payment Providers
- Search Engines
- External APIs
- Storage
- Messaging

Infrastructure depends on Domain.

Never the opposite.

---

# Business Logic

Business rules belong only inside:

- Entities
- Aggregates
- Domain Services

Never place business logic inside:

Controllers

Repositories

Database Queries

HTTP Middleware

DTOs

Utility Classes

---

# Service Responsibilities

Application Services

Coordinate business operations.

Domain Services

Implement domain behavior.

Infrastructure Services

Communicate with external systems.

Each service has exactly one responsibility.

---

# Repositories

Repositories provide persistence.

Repositories never contain business rules.

Repositories never implement workflows.

Repositories expose domain objects.

---

# DTO Usage

DTOs exist only for data transfer.

DTOs never contain business behavior.

DTOs should remain simple.

---

# Dependency Rules

Allowed

Controller

↓

Application

↓

Domain

↓

Infrastructure

Forbidden

Infrastructure

↓

Application

Domain

↓

Infrastructure

Presentation

↓

Database

---

# Module Communication

Modules communicate only through:

- Public interfaces
- Application services
- Domain Events

Never import internal implementation from another module.

---

# State Management

Business state belongs inside Aggregates.

Avoid shared mutable state.

Avoid global state.

---

# Transactions

Transactions begin in Application Services.

Never create transactions inside repositories.

Never span transactions across unrelated business operations.

---

# Error Handling

Business errors belong to Domain.

Infrastructure errors belong to Infrastructure.

Transport errors belong to Presentation.

Never mix error types.

---

# Validation

Transport validation

↓

Application validation

↓

Business validation

Each validation occurs exactly once.

---

# Logging

Business logic does not log.

Infrastructure logs technical operations.

Application logs workflows.

Audit logging has dedicated rules.

---

# Performance

Prefer correctness over optimization.

Optimize only after measurement.

Avoid premature optimization.

---

# Security

Security is mandatory.

Always:

Validate input.

Authorize actions.

Protect secrets.

Never trust client input.

---

# Code Reuse

Before creating:

Service

Repository

Handler

Utility

Validator

Always search for an existing implementation.

Reuse before creating.

---

# Anti-Patterns

Never create:

God Services

Fat Controllers

Anemic Domain Models

Static Business Classes

Hidden Dependencies

Cross-Module Database Access

Business Logic inside Controllers

Business Logic inside SQL

Shared Mutable State

Circular Dependencies

---

# Decision Rules

Before implementation ask:

Is this business logic?

If yes →

Domain.

Is this orchestration?

If yes →

Application.

Is this persistence?

If yes →

Infrastructure.

Is this HTTP?

If yes →

Presentation.

---

# Validation Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ Controller is thin.

✓ Business logic lives in Domain.

✓ Services have one responsibility.

✓ Dependencies point inward.

✓ No module boundaries are violated.

✓ No duplicated logic exists.

✓ Repository contains no business rules.

✓ Infrastructure depends on abstractions.

✓ DTOs contain no behavior.

✓ Architecture remains consistent.

